  "prompt": "When entering the US will I be detained for a bench warrant?",
  "response": "Whether or not you will be detained upon entering the US due to a bench warrant depends on several factors:\n\n**Factors that Increase the Likelihood of Detention:**\n\n*   **The nature of the warrant:**\n    *   **Criminal warrants:** These are much more likely to trigger detention. Serious crimes (felonies) will almost certainly lead to detention.\n    *   **Civil warrants:** These are less likely to trigger detention, but it's still possible, especially if related to issues like unpaid child support or failure to appear in court for a serious civil matter.\n*   **The jurisdiction that issued the warrant:**\n    *   **Federal warrants:** These are the most likely to be enforced at the border.\n    *   **State warrants:** Enforcement depends on whether the warrant is entered into national databases accessible by Customs and Border Protection (CBP). Many are, especially for more serious offenses.\n    *   **Local/County warrants:** These are the least likely to be enforced, but it's still possible if they've been entered into national databases.\n*   **The state you are entering:** Some states border each other and are more likely to be able to cooperate if there is a warrant.\n*   **Whether the warrant is \"extraditable\":** This means the issuing jurisdiction is willing to go to the effort and expense of extraditing you from another state (or country). Extradition is more likely for serious crimes.\n*   **Whether your name and identifying information match the warrant precisely:** A slight discrepancy could cause a delay, but it's unlikely to prevent enforcement if CBP is convinced it's you.\n*   **CBP's priorities:** CBP's focus shifts depending on national security concerns and other factors. They are more likely to focus on outstanding warrants at some times than at others.\n\n**Factors that Decrease the Likelihood of Detention:**\n\n*   **The warrant is old and for a minor offense:** Warrants can expire or become less of a priority over time.\n*   **The issuing jurisdiction is far away and unlikely to extradite:** Extradition can be expensive and time-consuming, so jurisdictions are less likely to pursue it for minor offenses or from distant locations.\n*   **The warrant is for a failure to appear for a very minor traffic violation:** These are less likely to be entered into national databases.\n\n**What Happens If You Are Detained:**\n\n*   **Verification:** CBP will verify the warrant and confirm that it is still active.\n*   **Detention:** You will be detained. The length of detention depends on the situation.\n*   **Notification of Issuing Jurisdiction:** CBP will notify the law enforcement agency that issued the warrant.\n*   **Extradition or Release:** The issuing jurisdiction will decide whether to extradite you. If they choose to extradite, you will be held until they arrange transportation. If they decline, you may be released, but this is not guaranteed. CBP could still have other reasons to deny you entry.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **CBP has broad authority:** CBP officers have significant discretion at the border. Even if a warrant is for a minor offense, they can still detain you if they have other concerns.\n*   **You have a right to remain silent:** If questioned about the warrant, you have the right to remain silent and request an attorney.\n*   **Be honest:** Do not lie to CBP officers. This is a crime and will make the situation worse.\n*   **Consult with an attorney:** If you know or suspect that you have a bench warrant, it is highly recommended to consult with a criminal defense attorney *before* attempting to enter the US. They can advise you on your rights and options and potentially help you resolve the warrant before you travel.\n\n**How to Find Out If You Have a Warrant:**\n\n*   **Contact the court clerk:** If you know the jurisdiction where you might have a warrant, contact the court clerk's office.\n*   **Hire an attorney:** An attorney can conduct a more thorough search for warrants on your behalf.\n*   **Online warrant searches:** Some jurisdictions have online warrant search tools, but these may not be comprehensive.\n\n**In summary, there is no definitive answer to whether you will be detained. It depends on the specific circumstances of the warrant and CBP's priorities. The best course of action is to address the warrant proactively before attempting to enter the US.**\n",
